Kiddi Kollege Inc. started from humble beginnings back in the mid 1950’s.  The owner, Geraldine Dolinar grew the business out of her own basement in Kansas City, Kansas. In the 1950s the words Childcare Center, Preschool, or even Daycare had yet to be spoken. The care of young children at that time usually fell to the local church or the domestic care giver. Few people thought about children’s education at such a young age in addition to their care, but Geraldine recognized this situation. She was not satisfied with the level of attention that the local children were receiving when it came to their education. At the time she had her third child (Her youngest daughter who is our current Regional Director), she saw an opportunity to the solve a problem in the local community, while also being able to care for her daughter.

During the late 1950’s another opportunity arose that helped this new venture gain traction: Women were entering the workforce and finding it hard to find care.  She networked with the women to in the community to find a sizable demand for women needing this service. She told the families of the community if she did decide to open a care center, that she would start an educational center, “a preschool… she would not be a babysitter”.  (Geraldine will correct anyone who calls Kiddi Kollege a Day Care to this day)

So, Geraldine decided to do it herself and develop an educational program. Ultimately, she became a entrepreneur while also giving her the option to care and educate her daughter. With her success she opened her first brick and mortar center in the mid 1960’s. She has always said that opening this business was one of her proudest accomplishments, and she was especially proud of opening up the business at a time when opportunities for women where scarce compared to today.

After opening her first center she started many traditions that set a standard among early education centers. To name a few, she had learning centers that included math, science, art, music, and manipulative play. Another tradition started at Kiddi Kollege is the preschool graduation. We conduct our preschool graduation every May. It is a great treat for the parents and every graduation is treasured by our parents and staff.

After the first center opened she continued to reinvest into her business later opening two more locations in Kansas City Kansas in the 1970’s. In the 1980’s she opened up two more locations in Olathe Kansas. The 6th & 7th Kiddi Kolleges where opened in Overland Park and Leawood. Now, the third Generation (Geraldine’s grandchildren) currently work in the centers and are looking ahead to the future, continuing to offer this valuable service to the community.

column11: Portside Learning Center's goal is to meet the social and emotional needs of young children at a time critical to their future happiness and success.  We strive to create a vital play based setting in which the children feel safe, challenged, and appreciated as individuals.  We view creative play as key to all the growth and learning that takes place during early childhood years.  A well-planned play space provides for a wide variety of experiences reflecting the child's natural interests and abilities.  Pre-school children learn best through repeated, concrete experiences involving as many of their senses as possible.  While offering structural activities for the children, we also believe in the importance of self directed, independent play, always remaining available to offer assistance and foster basic problem-solving skills.  We strive to provide a supportive, loving environment for the children, to encourage their growth in all areas, and to facilitate a successful transition between the early years at home with family and their future years ahead in school.

Maine Educational Center for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (MECDHH)/Governor Baxter School for the Deaf (GBSD) will provide high quality, state of the art services to students who are deaf and hard of hearing, their families and learning communities statewide.

Our Vision
The vision of MECDHH/GBSD is to expand and continually improve educational opportunities, programs and services for all children who are deaf and hard of hearing statewide. Our primary goal at Little Learners is to provide a safe, nurturing, and educational environment for children. We hope to stimulate the minds and imaginations of young children.

Little Friends is an Early Learning Center specializing in early childhood care and preschool education. The Center offers personalized care in a safe, clean environment. The curriculum is varied, age-appropriate and coupled with lots of indoor and outdoor play times. The playground features a wooden play system, clubhouse, protected sand play area in a spacious and natural backyard setting.

With 20 years of experience, Little Friends has demonstrated longevity with both staff and patrons. The staff is attentive and trained and has excellent references!

It is our purpose at Learning Tree to make every child successful aiding each child in the pursuit of excellence—to include qualities of self-worth, confidence, motivation, respect, empathy, caring and compassion, sharing and cooperative play, resolution to conflicts and problem solving, good communication, tolerance of others differences & age appropriate independence.

Our philosophy is to provide an environment rich in experiences, activities and opportunities promoting the development of the whole child through creative play and academic challenges building the foundations for happy, self confident, enthusiastic life-long learners. Research has shown that young children are concrete learners who need to see, taste, touch, smell,hear and move in order to understand the world around them. These experiences are promoted through activities that allow your child to learn through exploration and discovery.
Our primary goal is to treat each child as special and unique who actively learns at their own pace and learning style. The Learning Place fosters the growth of the whole child, emotionally, cognitively, socially, physically and creatively. Each day for your child is filled with wonder and excitement, rich with possibilities and smiling with accomplishments.

Our goal at Learning Land is to provide your child with a safe, comfortable and supportive learning environment. We will encourage your child to explore his or her surroundings with confidence and independence. Daily thematic activities are carefully designed by our experienced staff to foster your child's social and emotional development while providing an environment that promotes school readiness in a creative way.

We are a 5210 school, encouraging healthy habits for kids. In the interest of promoting school safety for all students, Learning Land is a nut free school.

We support children to understand themselves and their special place in this world through stressing the value of each child's individuality and creativity. Our mission is to provide rich and meaningful learning experiences in a safe and nurturing environment where children engage in activities to experience early learning success. At Leaps And Bounds Learning Center, we look forward to sharing in your child's growing years!

Harbor House Children's Center, the first licensed childcare center on Mount Desert Island, has been serving the families of our Island community since 1985. We provide quality care and early education for children ages 18 months to 5 years, whose parents live or work on MDI.

Whether it is playing with Legos, sharing a story with a cuddly friend or enjoying the fresh air in our large, natural PlayGarden, Harbor House Children’s Center provides a quality early care and education experience that will give your child a combination of guidance and freedom to grow and learn.

Our literacy based program is based on the State of Maine Early Childhood Learning & Infant Toddler Guidelines. We balance structured activities and free play so children can learn in the way they learn best - playing, exploring and having fun. Our goal is to provide the best care, help build a foundation of skills, and nurture a love of learning that will last a lifetime. We pride ourselves in the support we provide families for a successful transition to kindergarten.

Our spacious, light-filled classrooms and natural PlayGarden provide a wonderful learning environment for all ages. Whether creating a finger painting, listening to a story, growing vegetables in our garden or fishing from our child-sized lobster boat, the Children’s Center will nurture your child’s imagination, curiosity and excitement about learning.

Clover's intergenerational pre-school program emphasizes the concept that people come in a variety of sizes, ages and abilities. The sharing and exchanging of life experiences is as vital to structured elements of a well rounded education as letter and number recognition.

Clover kids interact with and learn along side their "grandfriends." Daily and weekly activities benefit both age groups. Art, music and free play enhance the more structured elements of pre-school learning, all with the goal of building a successful kindergarden experience. The enduring friendships that are formed between the children and residents offer lessons that last a lifetime.

column2: Circle Time Preschool And Day Care Center
column11:
Each child is an individual. We, here at Circle Time Preschool and Childcare, feel that meeting each child's needs is essential for growth. We are sensitive to a child's social, emotional, intellectual, and physical needs. Circle Time provides a literature based program through constant exposure to books, poems, songs and the written language. We also offer opportunities for children to explore, create, play and succeed with the use of activity centers, each with a different focus, such as art, science, and dramatic play areas.

Children have different learning styles and pass through the stages at different times. Our multi-level center provides children with the opportunities to develop concrete thinking and social skills as well as to create a positive self image.

Learning is an active process. Children learn through repeated exposure, role modeling, and the opportunity to apply and practice what they have learned. The use of hands-on experiences allows children to manipulate and investigate their surroundings. Using hands-on and manipulative materials in the classroom provides children with the opportunity to explore and create their own method of learning.

Our role, as educators, is to be a dynamic link between the children and the classroom and to create an environment which allows children to:

    -Be successful
    -Develop a positive self esteem
    -Grow through decision making
    -Create the skills and knowledge necessary to interact with      others
    -Relate their skills to their day-to-day experiences
    -Establish a love for learning

As teachers we present concrete models and experiences to help children visualize an idea or concept. We use the classroom environment to build communication skills, develop creative thinking, teach problem solving and develop use of judgment. Through the learning process, education prepares the children socially, emotionally and mentally for the challenges of life.

Children's Odyssey provides a content rich environment in which children learn through their active participation in a variety of hands-on, multi-modal experiences and social opportunities. These fun and inviting activities allow children to reach across domains to develop new skills by building and expanding upon existing ones. Intentional and incidental teaching occurs in an appropriate mix of individual, small, and large group instructional and freeplay opportunities, both indoors and out, to reflect best practice. Teacher’s knowledge, sensitivity, and responsiveness to children facilitates individual growth while fostering a sense of group belonging. A program for children ages birth to five and their families, Androscoggin Head Start and Child Care (AHSCC), is a federally funded program whose purpose is to promote children’s school readiness by enhancing their cognitive, social, and emotional development. Head Start provides children the opportunity to be successful in group settings while preparing them for academic success through quality learning environments which support children’s growth in

    language and literacy;
    cognition and general knowledge;
    physical development and health;
    social and emotional learning;

and approaches to learning. Our programs are designed to be inclusive of children with varying abilities and needs.

The comprehensive provided by Head Start/Early Head Start include education and cognitive development, health and nutrition services for the child, and family support and linkages to community social services for the family. Services are designed to be responsive to each child and family’s ethnic, cultural, and linguistic heritage.

The role of the parent as their child’s first and most important teacher is the foundation of developing a relationship between staff and the family. AHSCC staff builds relationships with families that support family’s well-being and positive parent-child relationship; families as learners and lifelong educators; family engagement in transitions; family connections to peers and community; and families as advocates and leaders.

Our program options include care that is sure to meet your needs and the needs of your child. Programs are designed for families who want to
strengthen their ability to improve their lives, the lives of their children, and increase school readiness skills. Use the links below to find a program that best fits your child and family needs.

    Preschool
    Home Based
    Extended Care

Please explore our website to learn more about the program and to see how we can serve you. You may also contact us by email info@androkids.com here.

column11: Eagles Nest Child Care is a Christ-Centered child care facility serving the Windham, Gorham, and Cumberland County area.

AIL bases its philosophy on each child's total development. We provide an enriching atmosphere which enables the child to develop socially, emotionally, physically and cognitively. We offer a learning environment which provides developmentally appropriate experiences designed to stimulate these areas of growth. The children are involved in first hand experiences and opportunities for self exploration and discovery. They are encouraged to explore the world around them through free play and directed activities. Learning through play is the heart of our curriculum. Daily lesson plans are introduced through structured themes with the children's interests in mind. Through individual and group activities children learn about themselves, others and the world around them.   

 Children develop and learn on an individual basis. Working with children in small groups enables them to receive the personalized attention they need to excel. AIL staff has the opportunity to observe and meet the individual needs of each child and to share those observations with parents. AIL offers each child the individual care, attention, nurturing and love, which is necessary for healthy growth. At AIL we value the individuality of each child by recognizing differences and offering personal care and attention in a group setting.

Involving families at AIL is a top priority. With parent involvement with our staff children understand and  make the strong connection between home and center. We are an extension of the family, developing a partnership where sharing support, ideas and genuine love for children is of the utmost importance. At AIL We encourage parents to visit and participate in school activities. At AIL we have an open door policy; which means you are more than welcome to come and go as you please.  Parents  are free to drop off or pick up your child any time during the day. You are also welcome to come visit, eat lunch, and go on field trips with your child's class.

column2: Wind In The Willows Country Preschool
column11:
Our curriculum focuses on developing pre-k skills and reading readiness  literacy skills.

Through fun games and activities your child will learn colors, shapes, counting to 20 and especially the alphabet letters and their sounds. 

Our basic kindergarten-readiness curriculum is “Letter of the Week.”  We explore each letter in many ways.  Young children learn best when they are active and using all their senses, so we’ll experience each letter not only by sight and sound, but also touch, taste and movement.  For example, during letter B week, we’ll have snacks of bananas, blueberries, bread and bagels, play with baseballs and basketballs;  in the science room we’ll read about bears, butterflies and beavers and in the art room working with brown and blue paint.  We’ll include exercise by jumping for j, dancing for d, marching for m, playing hopscotch and hula hoops for h, running a race for r and push-ups for p.

    Science is another curriculum area I’d like to focus on at Wind in the Willows.  The sciences curriculum includes animals, plants, seasons, weather and the environment.  We’ll talk about different kinds of animals, including mammals, reptiles, birds and insects, and where animals live, and what they eat, etc.  We’ll also learn about the 4 seasons and spend time outside observing the changes that occur with each season.  We have a short nature trail on the property and in good weather we’ll do a nature walk every day so the children can observe birds, collect leaves in the Fall, touch tree bark, etc.   In the Spring we will plant a school vegetable garden outside and each child will also get their own personal planter box, add soil and seeds and care for their plants.

column11:
At Sue's Place Child Care Center, our primary mission is to provide exemplary care for the children in our area by offering a model program tailored to ensure the quality of a child’s daily experiences. To provide a safe and developmentally rich environment for children while their families have to be away. Children are growing and learning many things. Our job is to guide them in their physical, mental and emotional growth while you are at work. They are not perfect (nor are they expected to be); they have good days and bad days, just like adults.

All children learn at different rates. They learn best through naturally occurring events, and through play and activities that provide for autonomy, control and as much practice or repetition as is necessary to master new skills and to learn to develop their own interests. A thoughtful combination of teacher directed, child initiated, and classroom routines constitute our program. The environment is set-up to help children learn: who they are, what they are capable of and being part of a group. Messages will be clear and consistent. We believe that your family is your child’s first and most important teacher. Your perspective and insights, goals and desires of your child are essential to our providing a great program for him or her. Parents are always a welcome addition to our program.

Additionally, we believe that a learning environment that fosters respect for cultural diversity and that utilizes an open approach to education allows for optimal growth and development of your children.

We have the highest respect for children and their ability to progress through their childhood, developing at a steady pace. We strive to offer routines, activities and an atmosphere of fun and challenge.

The classroom curriculum, rooted in Biblical principles and virtues, helps children develop physically, intellectually, emotionally and socially. The trend in education is to keep children who are developmentally at-risk and/or disabled in regular classrooms by means of new teaching methodologies rather than referring them immediately for special education.

In order to keep at-risk children and children with special needs in regular classrooms, the entire learning environment is being changed.  Usually teachers will subgroup students into small working units.  Sometimes a physical therapist or an occupational therapist or a speech language pathologist may enter the classroom to work with the teacher and specific children.  At-risk students have materials that are modified to meet their individual learning needs requiring individual teacher time and attention. The whole class participates in a process to help all children succeed in their education.

With all of this in mind, regular education and special education have been changing, slowly but surely.  The traditional regular classroom that most parents remember no longer exists.  It is important for parents to speak to their children about the fact that there may be not only new friends in class, but also special friends.  The diversity in regular classrooms has increased dramatically as children with at-risk learning needs or special needs remain in regular classrooms for longer periods of time.*

Circle of Learning was established in 2001 as a developmental preschool to help any two and a half to five year olds be ready for public school.  We serve children with a wide variety of disabilities as well as typically developing children when space has been available.  Circle of Learning has long recognized that one of the best ways to instruct special needs children is to have them learn with typically developing peers.  Our classroom on the University’s Presque Isle campus is an Inclusive Preschool where we will be offering a less restrictive learning environment for special needs children along with a typical preschool program for the faculty and students of UMPI as well as Presque Isle area children.  We are offering a morning only session and an all day session with afterschool care until 5pm.  For more information or to set up an appointment to enroll your child please contact Lindy Boinske, Family Support Specialist at 493-3055.

The Mill School offers a learning community for
homeschooling children ages five to twelve.
Children at The Mill School attend school three days a week at the beautifully renovated mill in Freedom, Maine. There are twenty children and two teachers in the class.

The children are given authentic, developmentally appropriate opportunities for expanding their skills. The younger children are given time to focus on the work of the young child: exploration and play. They are also gently introduced to academics. The older children participate in literacy and math workshops each day.

Welcome to Maine Mountain Children’s House. We are a Montessori preschool in Kingfield, Maine, just south of Sugarloaf Mountain and Carrabassett Valley.  We offer an educational experience encouraging each child to grow academically, emotionally and socially while fostering independence, respect, and responsibility to self, others, and the Earth.

Maine Mountain Children’s House is offering a 5 full days, 5 half days, 3 full days, or 3 half days in a Montessori environment. Childcare is also available to students before or after their public school day. Our school calendar will follow the local district (M.S.A.D. #58) school calendar.

Please email, phone, text or find us on Facebook if you have any questions about our program. Also be sure to check out our links to the right to familiarize yourself with the Montessori teaching philosophy.

column2: Broadreach Family & Community Services - Weymouth Elementary
column11: We believe that all children and families have basic rights, including: the right to early intervention and an appropriate education through the least restrictive means; the right to nutritional food, medical care, and safe and warm housing; and the right to love and be loved and to receive a fair chance at succeeding in life. We strive to uphold these rights for children and families. They deserve nothing less.

column2: Broadreach Family & Community Services - Stockton Springs Element
column11: We believe that all children and families have basic rights, including: the right to early intervention and an appropriate education through the least restrictive means; the right to nutritional food, medical care, and safe and warm housing; and the right to love and be loved and to receive a fair chance at succeeding in life. We strive to uphold these rights for children and families. They deserve nothing less.

Walk through our doors and you will find a warm inviting child friendly space, influenced by the 100 year old teachings of Maria Montessori. Our classroom is rich in sunshine, natural wood and classroom materials unique to the Montessori approach. Our classroom will provide the structure children need to develop self discipline along with a sense of self which will be life sustaining.

Grace Montessori will offer your child opportunities to develop strong skills in math and reading. It is also strong in helping children develop independence as well as grace and courtesy. Your child will also learn about the world through use of maps, exploring cultures and the animals unique to each continent.
Grace Montessori
We will be offering lessons in foreign language, art and music through a specialist whose own children grew up with a Montessori experience. Here at Grace Montessori, we also strongly believe in connecting children with their natural environment. They will learn not only about themselves but also have firsthand experience in learning the strong connection between all living things. As they develop these skills, they will experience and understand how each of us has a role to play in our classroom, our environment and the world.

In my experience, I have found no other approach to education that puts as much emphasis on supporting the child to learn these important life sustaining lessons as much as learning traditional concepts such as math, reading, geography and science. It is the Montessori Approach that has given me permission and construct to teach the way I knew in my heart to be right, nurturing the whole child, mind, body and spirit. This is why I am so passionate about calling myself a Montessori Educator.
–Katherine Johnston, MEd.

Grace Montessori also includes a faith based perspective to their understanding. This includes prayer, faith based discussions and opportunities for each child to discover and build their own personal relationship with God.

YMCAs are dedicated to providing high-quality, affordable child care. As the nation’s largest provider of child care programs, YMCAs provide family-centered, values-based programs to nurture children’s healthy development. 

 

Well-trained staff provide safe, affordable, high-quality care so you can have peace of mind while you work. Like all Y programs, child care is open to all, with financial aid available. Staff members are partners with parents and other caregivers, working together to help kids grow up healthy, happy and strong.

Your child will learn, grow and thrive at the Penobscot Bay YMCA Child Care Center. Children are encouraged to learn new skills and freely express themselves while exploring their environment. Our dedicated teachers are partners with parents and other caregivers, working together to fully support your child’s individual needs.

Mission Statement: KCCHC seeks to create a healthy Knox County for all
community members and to work collaboratively with all sectors of the
Maine Public Health Infrastructure to achieve this mission.

Vision: The Knox County Community Health Coalition (KCCHC) will
identify, recommend and assist efforts to enhance the overall quality of life
and health in Knox County. KCCHC will assess and monitor the health of
our communities, identifying populations at risk of health problems,
providing health promotion and disease prevention services, and access to
cost-effective healthcare. KCCHC will promote a livable wage for all
community members, work to reduce substance abuse, create
opportunities for individuals to empower themselves, improve affordable
transportation and communicate effectively with each other on common
concerns.

column11:
Head Start is a comprehensive program for children from birth to age five and expectant families. The goal of Head Start is to nurture future success for children and families by providing education, support and resources.
Community Concepts has won national awards of excellence for its Head Start program.
At Community Concepts, we believe that each child has unique and individual talents and interests. Our teachers honor these differences by providing each child with individualized attention and activities so they may learn and grow at their own pace.

Our purpose is twofold:

column2: CHILDRENS CENTER: EARLY INTERVENTION & FAMILY SUPPORT
column11:
The Children’s Center Early Intervention and Family Support is a specialized provider of services in central Maine for young children with developmental delays and disabilities such as pervasive developmental disorder, intellectual disability, cerebral palsy, Down syndrome, autism, and more.   We provide a continuum of center-based therapies and care for young children with disabilities that is simply not offered in this same format anywhere else in the region.   The Children's Center has been providing services for children with special needs and their families since 1966. 

The Center’s primary facility operates in Augusta, Maine, and provides early intervention and pediatric therapies (speech and language therapy, occupational therapy, and mental health services) in an inclusive, learning-rich child care environment, to children from six weeks to six years of age.  Our targeted case management, community-based behavioral health professionals, and parent and provider education programs serve families of children with special needs (through age 12) in Kennebec and Somerset Counties. We have a satellite office in Skowhegan providing multiple family services, and we provide services (BHP, TCM) and programs (a Relatives as Parents Program, the “Grandest Parents”) in Waterville, as well.

column11: Educare Winnebago is the first Educare School to serve Native American children and families. The school combines Educare's best practices with activities that honor local culture and traditions. Children are taught in the native Ho-Chunk language in addition to English. A cultural resource room houses events, community college classes and after-school tutoring programs for K-3rd grade students from Winnebago Public Schools. Educare Winnebago is located on the Winnebago Indian Reservation in northeast Nebraska.

column11: At Busy Bee’s Child Care Center, we take pride in providing a clean, caring and like-home atmosphere where children can explore and develop to their full potential. Busy Bee’s Child Care Center was founded in 2010, and is family owned and operated.  We believe that play is the means by which young children learn. Busy Bee’s Child Care Center is committed to promoting the growth of the whole child by providing an environment that attends to each child’s physical, emotional, social, and intellectual development. The children are encouraged to make choices and develop independence while learning.

Preschoolers will learn in our age appropriate, center style school, allowing children to grow in all areas. The Y’s preschool uses The Creative Curriculum which is based on the latest research that birth to 5 are the most important years in a child’s life. The child’s developmental areas: physical, social/emotional, cognitive, and language will grow in the Y’s safe, nurturing environment. The program promotes reading skills, along with using Handwriting without Tears. Our 5 year olds graduate kindergarten ready. Swimming and gym time is provided.

We are a curriculum based program that serves children from 6 weeks to 12 years old. Each child experiences age-appropriate learning opportunities through structured curriculum development. The children are provided with developmental classrooms set up to promote hands on learning. We focus on each child and their individual needs to ensure their development is always challenged.

Our childcare prepares children for kindergarten focusing on providing a full day care experience for your child. We believe in low student teacher ratios, and a highly trained Christian staff.

At Happy Sprouts Child Development Center, you will find a warm and welcoming environment for your child to learn, grow, and experience the joys of childhood. From developing infants and curious toddlers to exploring preschoolers, our teachers understand the balance between nurturing young minds and caring for tender hearts.

More than childcare, Happy Sprouts Child Development Center offers experiences that build on the individual strengths and talents of young children while providing the care they need and the learning experiences they enjoy.

Parents go to work knowing their children are happy, safe, and well cared for.

Y Kids Club is a state licensed school aged child care program offered in the following Norfolk Public Elementary Schools in Norfolk, Nebraska – Bel Air, Jefferson, Montessori at Lincoln, Westside, and Woodland Park.

Y Kids Club provides Before and After School Child Care at the schools. Before Care begins as early as 6 am until school begins, and After Care begins as soon as school is dismissed until 6 pm. Y Kids Club is also available from 6 am – 6 pm at the YMCA on School Out Days, Holiday Break Days, Snow Days, and Summer (Day Camp) – these days are open to anyone in grades K-6th; child does not have to be in the Y Kids Club program to participate.

Monthly Calendars are always available at each Kids Club location, the YMCA Information Center, and on our website (see right column). Please note the days your child comes to the Y for swimming and other activities!

column2: BENNINGTON FOUNDATION BEFORE AND AFTER SCHOOL
column11:
The Bennington Public Schools Foundation All Star Kids Program is a self-supporting project offered in each elementary school building in the Bennington School District.  All net proceeds from the All Star Kids program are earmarked for the Foundation’s benevolent programs within the Bennington Public Schools, including classroom grants and scholarships. All Star Kids provides quality, reliable child care with the convenience of an in-school location at a competitive child care price.

Each site location exceeds Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services standards for Child Care Centers as well as meeting inspection requirements from the Fire Marshal and County Health Department. The program attends to educational and nutritional needs of each child by providing breakfast and afternoon snacks and large muscle activities supplemented with fine motor skill activities such as arts and crafts and table games. Children will also have opportunities to complete school assignments, read, have free choice time, and participate in outdoor play. All Star Kids management and personnel are dedicated to providing a fun, safe, and enriching childcare experience for each family enrolled in the All Star Kids program.

The All Star Kids program provides each child a fun, safe and familiar environment, while offering new opportunities for learning, social development, and recreation. All Star Kids offers  flexible schedule options at an affordable price. Year round programs that operate during regular school days, non-school days, and during summer break are available.

Committed to creating great work environments for its 18,000 employees, the company has been named 12 times as one of FORTUNE magazine's "Best Companies to Work for in America."

Bright Horizons provides work/life solutions for more than 800 leading employers to help them address challenges across key life stages. Programs include child care, back-up care, college counseling, elder care, and work/life consulting.

The first few years of life are an extraordinary time that sets the stage for all the years that follow. Our program for learning creates educational environments that empower children to be confident, successful, lifelong learners and socially responsible citizens. Bright Horizons' innovative programs help children, families, and employers work together to be their very best.

Psalms 127:3 Child Care Ministry has been serving the community for over 10 years. Our approach is to attend to all of a child's needs, not just a selected few, is the most effective method we have discovered to promoting the development of the "whole" child. For this reason we carefully and thoughtfully attend to each child’s spiritual, physical, socio-emotional, intellectual and mental needs.

Much like a flower, a child will grow and mature to a limited extent regardless of whether or not their specific needs are met. But by nurturing the whole child, we can ensure the child blossoms in every area of their development and begin to help each child release their God given potential.

column2: OUR LADY OF LOURDES EXT. CARE

column11:
We believe that every child needs and deserves the best possible care while his parents are working or going to school, especially those with special needs. We accept children with all types of physical, mental, emotional and behavioral disorders.  If you are in need of loving child care, we can help.  The founder and executive director of Precious Memories Child Care is Verna Kephart.  She has been caring for Omaha's children for over 40 years.  She has raised three biological children, two step children and many foster children through the years.  She is still raising two children that she adopted from the center with special needs who are now teenagers.

Precious Memories Child Care is the life's work of a group of dedicated people who create a family atmosphere of love and care.  This non-profit care center is helped thorugh the generous people who care.

In Omaha’s child advocacy community, Verna Kephart is named as one of the difference-makers in the lives of disadvantaged children.  The children lovingly call her "Grandma Verna". She has cared for disadvantaged and special needs children for almost 50 years, opening Precious Memories child care center at 25th and Leavenworth Streets more than 20 years ago.  To watch a photo slide show of Precious Memories Click Here.

The dedicated staff cares for up to 100 children. About half of the children are in foster care, removed from their homes because of severe neglect and abuse. Others are struggling with autism, fetal alcohol syndrome, lead poisoning or birth defects.

Covenant Kids Preschool began in the fall of 2009. We currently offer morning classes throughout the week from 9:00 am to 12:00 noon for children ages three until they begin Kindergarten.
The Busy Bees class is designed for children ages 3 and 4-year-olds and meets on Tuesdays and Thursdays.

The Superstars group is made up of 4 and 5-year-old children and meets on Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays.

Our High-Five Heroes class is designed for children five-year-olds who are awaiting Kindergarten meets Monday through Friday during the school year.

We follow the Millard Schools attendance calendar schedule for meeting days and for days off during the school year.

At Hamilton Heights, we work hard every day to create a warm and nurturing environment that is necessary for learning, growing and developing. We want every aspect of our service not only to meet, but also to exceed your family’s needs.  We want to ensure that Hamilton Heights is not only the right place for your child, but also the right place for you.

Stonebridge Christian Preschool first opened in 1992 with two small classes held at Fort Street Christian Church on 99th and Fort Street. Over the years, the church has grown and moved to 156th and Butler Avenue, and the preschool has grown as well. For 2014-2015, we will offer 10 different class options for children ages 2-6. We offer fun, creative, and educational activities that help children grow and learn.  We provide a Christian environment where children grow in their love for Jesus, and also in their life and learning skills. The children engage in learning centers that are designed to strengthen skills in math, language and literacy, dramatic play, music and movement, art, manipulatives, and imaginative play. column11:
At Children’s Express Childcare & Learning Center you’ll find experienced, well-trained teachers and stimulating activities where your child will be exposed to numbers, letters, and shapes. More importantly, they learn how to socialize, they make friends and learn to share and contribute. Your children will enter kindergarten with better pre-reading skills, richer vocabularies and stronger basic math and science skills.

Our program teaches kids how to be students. Your child will learn how to raise his/her hand, take turns, and share the teacher’s attention. Furthermore, he/she will learn how to separate from Mommy or Daddy! All of this makes for an easier transition to kindergarten. Kindergarten Teachers will tell you that the students who are ready to learn are those who come into school with good social and behavioral skills.

Children’s Express provides a place where your child can gain a sense of self, explore, play with his/her peers and build confidence. Kids in preschool discover that they are capable and can do things for themselves from small tasks to tackling bigger issues; like making decisions about how to spend their free time.

The skills a child learns at the early stages provide the foundation for all other skills that will be learned throughout life.

Trained and experienced Preschool Teachers are crucial to a successful preschool experience. For many children, preschool colors the way they will forever look at school; it is this first experience which will foster a lifelong love of learning and an overall sense of comfort and achievement within the preschool environment. Our Teachers will often take basic concepts and incorporate them into play. Children at this age learn through play concepts that incorporate all of their senses. While they are having fun and practicing essential social concepts such as being respectful of each other, taking turns, etc., they are unaware that they are even absorbing educational concepts. Our teachers are able to engage each child and offer lessons through these playful avenues. The most important qualification for preschool teachers is the ability to instill a joy of learning that stays with their young students for a lifetime!

The Children’s Express All Aboard curriculum is organized into theme based centers that address topics which encourage children to develop their skills and confidence. Each center incorporates language, math, science, creative arts, music, motor skills and social development.
Our mission is to provide a rich Christian environment for children to grow in all areas of development and to know Jesus as their Savior and friend.

column11: Located in the prestigious “Gold Coast” district, the House of Montessori enjoys an enviable historic address near downtown Omaha and medical center. St. Margaret Mary School, a private Catholic elementary school, has been educating children in the metropolitan community of Omaha, Nebraska, for almost 100 years.  The school, established in 1921 by the Sisters of Mercy of the Americas, serves kindergarten through eighth grades.  In 1924, Monsignor Joseph Suneg, a devout priest and talented wood carver, became the pastor and administrator.  He opened the doors of the present school in 1951 and stayed until his retirement in 1969. His legacy still touches the lives of students as much today as it did in 1951.

As one of 32 elementary metropolitan schools of the Archdiocese of Omaha, Nebraska, St. Margaret Mary serves the needs of 535 students from its location in the central part of the city.  A 2 1/2 year renovation and expansion project of the school and parish began in 1996, with school improvements including mechanical and electrical renovations, as well as the addition of an elevator, administrative offices, handicapped accessibility, two computer labs, a new resource library, a music room, and a science lab. In 2007, a geothermal heating and air conditioning system, plus new thermal paned windows were added to the school building.

The foundation for such interaction is the St. Margaret Mary parish community, who is committed both spiritually and financially to the achievement of this philosophy.  Our desire is to encourage each member of the Saint Margaret Mary community to become personally responsible to God, self, family, and country.  Within this environment, it is the purpose of St. Margaret Mary School to produce happy, successful, active members of the Body of Christ and the community.

In 2008 St. Margaret Mary School was designated a Blue Ribbon School by the U.S. Department of Education.

As we continue the second decade of the millennium, we are charged with the task of producing students who will be equipped to work and live in a global society that will demand much from them.  They will need to be members of the Body of Christ who are spiritually, emotionally, morally, intellectually, physically, socially and technologically equipped to live their lives based on the Gospel values and the Catholic Tradition.

As dedicated educators, the staff ensures student success becasue our greatest source of pride comes from the success and accomplishments of our students!

We'd invite you to please stop by and visit our school. We know you will feel an excitement and energy when you arrive!  Our school is a place of joy for the children and the adults who enter our doors each day. At Neihardt, “joy” is firmly rooted in the nurturing, positive classrooms and cultivated by caring, professional staff members, as well as actively involved parents.
 
Our school is a place of continuous learning for children as well as adults.  We offer learning environments designed to motivate and guide all students to achieve their greatest potential. You will find a commitment here: to learning, achievement, growth…a commitment to each and every child. 

Many of you have heard the African Proverb, "It takes a whole village to raise a child".  It refers to the need of an extended family to raise children, a most precious gift. As families we need to rely on the communal effort it takes in growing a child! At Neihardt, we are honored to be a part of your village!

Immanuel Evangelical Lutheran Church has been a part of the Lincoln community since October 17, 1909. Established as a mission congregation to meet the spiritual needs of the many Germans from Russia who had migrated into Lincoln’s South Bottoms neighborhood, Immanuel has a long and storied history.

Immanuel is people with a mission. Our mission statement is simple: “One beggar showing other beggars where to find bread.” We implement that mission without tricks or gimmicks. Our pastor simply preaches and teaches that Jesus Christ, the Son of God, was crucified for the sins of every man, woman and child — and by His death, we have forgiveness, life, and salvation.


We invite you to come and visit us. Join with us and hear the historic liturgy of the Christian Church, sing Christ-centered hymns to the sound of an organ, and be fed by God’s Word and Sacraments. Come to Immanuel and receive the bread of eternal life and hear the sweet message that you are forgiven in the name of the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit.

Danbury and Lebanon School Districts combined their students at the beginning of the 1958-1959 school year to form the Beaver Valley School District.

The Indianola and the Red Willow School Districts met as a combined school district on June 26, 1969 to hold the first school board meeting for the newly formed Republican Valley School District.  Beginning with the 1969-1970 school year, students combined to form the Republican Valley Schools.

The Wilsonville School District combined with the Beaver Valley School District on September 1, 1983.  An elementary attendance center remained in Wilsonville until the mid-90’s.

The Bartley and Beaver Valley School Districts officially became the Twin Valley School District on March 1, 1997.  An elementary attendance center remained at the building in Danbury with Junior-Senior High students combining for the 1997-1998 school year in Bartley.

The Marion School District decided to close the doors of their K-8 district and combine with the Twin Valley District on August 1, 1998 following state legislation ruling Class I school districts affiliate with a kindergarten-grade twelve district.

The Twin Valley and Republican Valley School districts legally merged on August 1, 2003 following a majority vote of the patrons of both districts on March 25, 2003 to issue bonds to build a new building in Bartley and merge both districts.  The Twin Valley fourth grade students were transported to the Republican Valley Elementary School in Indianola for the 2003-2004 school year, and the district’s preschool was located in Bartley.  A cooperative agreement between both districts allowed students participating in cross country, junior high sports, track and golf to combine during the 2003-2004 school year.  

On October 13, 2003, the Board of Education approved the newly formed district’s name and mascot as the Southwest Public School Roughriders.  A motion by the School Board on November 10, 2003 approved the school colors as navy blue, Carolina blue, and white.  The school name, mascot, and colors were approved following a vote of the student body.  The remaining grades of each district officially began classes as one district for the 2004-2005 school year with grades six through eight located at the Bartley site and grades nine through twelve at the rural Republican Valley High School site.  Elementary students will continue to receive their education at the building in the City of Indianola.  The final drawing of the official Roughrider mascot was approved at the February 9, 2004 Board of Education meeting.  Contractors began work on the new building site at Bartley in March of 2008.  Occupation of the new building took place on November 13, 2009.

Westmoor Elementary is the largest and only single level elementary school in Scottsbluff. The building opened in the fall of 1960 and added a six room pod addition in 1968. Six more classrooms and air conditioning were added in August 2009. In 2011, Westmoor celebrated 50 years of successful education with a community open house.

With and enrollment of just over 400 students, Westmoor has three  to four sections of each grade with classroom sizes ranging from 16-23 students. The building is fortunate to house the districts Multi-Categorical Special Education Program, which consists of three additional classrooms. The inclusion of special needs students develops a caring and accepting attitude of people's differences in all students.

Westmoor students utilize the Accelerated Reader and the Accelerated Math programs. These two programs are supplementary to the regular reading and math curriculum and provide excellent differentiation for all students. Students that master math objectives and reading levels earn certificates and awards. As a result of excellent curriculum and teaching, Westmoor students have met the Adequate Yearly Progress goals as set by federal legislation, No Child Left Behind, and boast one of the highest percentages of high ability learners in the district.

In spite of the size of the building, it truly functions as a family. You can tell when you walk in the front door, it is a child-centered environment.

Park Center Daycare opened on June 4th, 2012. Most people in Elgin remember the building as the old Park Center School. The School was located 10 miles west of Elgin on highway 70. Several years after the school closed it was moved into Elgin by the Historical Society ('98). It sits on a lot on Bowen street right off highway 14. The building was in rough shape and screaming for some much needed attention. My Husband and I began talking about the need for more daycare in Elgin. I have a 4 year old son and we had just had a son and I was wanting to work closer to home. We started throwing around the idea of opening a daycare center in Elgin. Bruce said he knew the perfect place. We spoke with a member of the Historical Society and she said that they were talking about selling the building. When I first seen the building I didn't know what to think. The inside was almost as bad as the outside. But I guess I underestimated my Husband alittle. We purchased the building and began the remodel at the end of February. In no time the project took off!!! I was amazed at how quickly it began to look like a daycare. Our initial thought for an opening date was July 1st, but we were so far ahead of schedule we moved our opening date to June 4th!! We figured the building had sat empty for long enough we were anxious to say the least to get kids running and playing in the building once again! Now we have been open for 4 months and things are going great. We have new children enrolling about every week and we always have room for drop ins. It is hard to find a job that you like and very rare to find one that you love so I consider myself a very lucky person because I love what I do!!

At the YMCA of Greater Omaha, strengthening community is our cause. Strong communities are the result of steady leadership and stewardship of strong values, which is what the Y is all about. We make life changing impact to the children, adults and families we serve through programs that focus on three key areas: youth development, healthy living and social responsibility.

As an organization, we strive to understand our community needs. We provide services and programs that cater specifically to the issues our children, families and neighborhoods face.  Through crucial partnerships with over 150 not-for-profit agencies, schools and organizations we are working hard to reach as many people as possible and making a lasting difference.

The Y is open to all people regardless of their ability to pay for programs and services, and as a result we provide over $1,000,000 of financial assistance each year.  By investing in our kids, our health and our neighbors, the YMCA of Greater Omaha ensures that everyone, regardless of age, income or background, has the opportunity to thrive—thereby strengthening our community.

Throughout the year, the NOLC acts as a safe haven, serving hundreds of low-income youth after school, and on weekends—the hours our children are most at risk of developing negative behaviors. The NOLC has served more than three thousand young people over the past forty-two years--approximately 97% of our children have not had contact with the court system. 

 The NOLC's programs are nationally recognized for their success in building strong character, social values, 

and resiliency to drugs and alcohol. Former President George H. Bush named the NOLC the nation's 535th Point of Light in 1991. The late Joe Edmonson, NOLC's co-founder and director, received local, state, and national honors for his service to the youth of Omaha, including the Ike Friedman Community Service Award by the Knights of AK-SAR-BEN, the Otto Swanson Spirit of Service Award, and an honorary doctorate in humanitarian service from Creighton University. 

 All youth need adult role models who can inspire. By participating in the NOLC's activities and programs, inner city youth come in regular contact with compassionate, capable adults--NOLC's staff, coaches, recreation and computer aides, tutors, and community volunteers who offer support, guidance, and the encouragement to succeed in school and life. These mentor relationships allow the NOLC to steer its youth in positive social, academic, and vocational directions, and also provide the means for staff to proactively monitor each student's progress.

column2: TINY HANDS, BIG DREAMS  CHILD DEVELOPMENT CENTER,
column11:
Tiny Hands, Big Dreams will provide care for children 6 weeks to 12 years of age, offering transportation to area schools and a fun-filled summer program!

Our center is set up to provide each age group their own classroom to allow the best and most effective learning and care environment possible. Each classroom will have a daily schedule and a teacher-created curriculum developed by using professional resources!

Infants 6 weeks to 18 months will have a variety of age appropriate toys and activities to keep them busy and learning throughout each day. Their daily routine will offer plenty of time for younger infants to take advantage of our mats for tummy time and play, while the older infants will have walking toys and activities to keep them busy!

Our toddler room is one of the busiest! A variety of imaginative and educational toys are at their disposal as they grow and learn during this crucial stage of development! Monthly and weekly themes are followed throughout the center, with each classroom interpreting the theme in their own creative way.

Preschool One is an amazing place for your child to continue growing and learning, developing interests and pursuing them using their imagination and the vast resources we have available for them. Our preschool class will begin working on letter and number recognition, as well as continuing their development in social skills through active play!

Our Pre-K programs are full of developmental toys and materials to help your child develop social and educational skills and prepare them for kindergarten! Our weekly schedule in these classrooms entail use of manipulatives, reading and writing time, dramatic play, and of course, our weekly theme activities!

School age children will have a hard time being bored here! Tiny Hands is stocked with a large variety of games, activities, books, and programs that will keep your school age child entertained daily! During the school year, we will have a Homework Club available to help children complete homework and excel to the best of their abilities! In the summer, field trips will be taken 3-5 times per week to libraries, swimming pools, children's museums, movies, city parks, and Mahoney State Park! On days field trips are not taken, our school age class will be able to spend time as teacher's helpers, playing on our playground, performing science experiments, conducting cooking projects and much more!

The Adult Learning Center will continue to excel as an educational agency designed to provide the academic skills, job training and support services needed for adults and young adults to achieve more productive lives for themselves and their children.
Goal
Statements

The goals of the Adult Learning Center have been formulated to respond to identified community needs:

    To assist young adults and adults to increase their basic educational and life coping skills by providing academic programs.
    To prepare individuals for the local workplace by providing pathways from school to work, job training, or higher education.
    To assist individuals to cope with social, family and work issues by providing community education programs to the community at large.
    To assist adults and young adults to participate in education, job training programs, and the workforce by providing needed support services of family literacy, childcare, school age care and parenting.
    To maintain staff excellence by attracting, training, and retaining committed, certified, creative educators and support staff.
    To maintain a financial position that responds to Adult Learning Center priorities.

All of the Center’s programs and services will reflect these goals.

column11:
Small Wonders Family Child Care "To learn and explore with new friends" Small Wonders Family Child Care, located in Lisbon, opened its doors in 1993 as a license exempt child care and became licensed in 2000. Kathy Wright, owner and director, has envisioned a thoughtful, purposeful environment for the children and families at the center. Her ideas became reality this year upon the completion of her newly renovated, custom designed child care space. Small Wonders has a Bartering Payment Assistance Program which allows parents to use their skills within their profession in exchange for child care time for their family. When a parent, (fondly referred to as Mr. Bill) lost his job, Kathy’s family hired him to repair their camper. They were then able to sell the camper and use the money to pay Mr. Bill to do carpentry work at the child care. Mr. Bill gave them a discounted rate for his services. As a result, Mr. Bill’s children, who had been at Small Wonders since infancy, were able to remain at the center, and the Small Wonders environment could become what it is today: custom made cubbies in a large, open welcome area, a room specifically for afterschool children, many built-ins such as a dollhouse with different textures and colors on every level, bench seating, bookshelves, a puzzle shelf, a magic castle, and so much more.

We encourage you to visit the Small Wonders Family Child Care website at http://smallwondersfcc.weebly.com to see photos of the center and to learn more about the program. Please note that some areas of the website are password protected for safety. Congratulations to Small Wonders Family Child Care!

column11: Moultonborough Learning Center seeks to provide quality child care for children in the Lakes Region. Children will be provided quality child care, have the opportunity to learn, explore and grow.

At first glance, our school may appear to be small but once you take a closer look you’ll see our mission is big. In fact it may even appear to be growing! The Children’s Greenhouse offers a unique approach to fostering the development of the whole child. Rather than focusing on what the child is learning we focus on how the child is learning.
    We do this is by providing children with quality experiences that nurture their natural curiosity to learn.  Our children are never confined to tables when lessons are implemented. Classroom curriculums aren’t ever limited to one particular theme. Children aren’t told to stop working on an activity they’ve made progress on because their activity time has ended. Our teachers will never take away opportunities for the children to learn from their mistakes by offering only moderate challenges and intervening at the first signs of frustration.
   At The Children’s Greenhouse we recognize that each child is unique, which is why our mission is unique. Our teachers use an emergent curriculum, and our classrooms have been thoughtfully designed to foster growth and teach every child to be resourceful, take initiative, innovate, adapt, and be inspired by overcoming challenges.
    The Children’s Greenhouse encourages parents to come in and observe our classrooms, meet our dedicated staff, and experience The Children’s Greenhouse first hand.  We are looking forward to partnering with the children and families of Merrimack and its surrounding communities, and hope a visit will captivate and inspire your curiosity!

The Kinder Center is the ideal program for ½ day kindergarten care needs! Morning Kindergartners are picked up from school and bussed to Hampshire Hills where they have their lunch and a little relaxation period. Then it's off to enjoy swimming lessons in our beautiful, warm pools, tennis, field sports at The Hampshire Dome, climbing and play on our three outdoor playgrounds. Specialty games, learning games, and craft activities are among the many other choices your child will enjoy. Pick up is between 3:30 and 4:00 pm. Later pick up is also available. Kids join our junior division of the FAST program. Additional program fees apply.

Welcome to Play Laugh N’ Grow Childcare & Pre-school Center. We currently have two locations, one in Raymond, NH and our new location opening soon at 184 raymond rd, Chester, NH. Our goal is to provide a safe, happy, and nurturing environment for your child to learn and grow throughout their younger years. Our program encourages physical, emotional and intellectual development, as well as instilling a love of learning! Each classroom is bright and cheerful, with many of the essential tools to promote learning with a teacher that will nurture and guide your child to become an independent and thoughtful learner! Play Laugh N' grow is a childcare and Pre-school  that was founded by Kristy and Kevin DeCesare in August of 2009. Play Laugh N' Grow provides high quality child care for children, ages 6 weeks to 6 years. We have established a developmentally appropriate curriculum for early education through programs that offer intellectually challenging experiences, and many opportunities to develop social relationships. From the moment you enter our school, its unique atmosphere is evident. Here at Play Laugh N' Grow we have created an environment where learning is a process – a series of experiences beginning the very first moment your child enters our center, whether they be six weeks old, or six years!

column2: East Derry Memorial School Extended Day Program
column11:
East Derry Memorial Elementary is a kindergarten through grade five school located in a residential area of Derry, NH.  It has a student enrollment of about 415 children served by a faculty of about seventy dedicated and energetic people. Class sizes range from 18-25 children depending upon grade.


The curriculum includes math, reading, writing, language arts, science and social studies.  In addition, children  receive instruction  in technology, art, music, physical education and library.  Literacy is orchestrated using the “Reader's Workshop” framework. In mathematics, EDMES will be piloting a few different programs this year. A couple of grade levels will continue to use  the "Four Frames" framework, which we have been using for years.  The school’s PACE program provides enrichment and additional challenge to students.  Help is available at all grade levels through our Remedial Reading, English as a Second Language  and Special Education departments.  To gather data to help inform instruction, the Developmental Reading and Northwest Evaluation Association Assessments are administered to students at various times during the school year. East Derry Memorial is also  a member of the Positive Behavioral Interventions and Supports  (PBIS) network, and as such, we hold very high expectations for the  respect, responsibility and safety displayed by the members of our school community.


The school’s faculty participates regularly in a variety of professional development opportunities provided by the Derry Cooperative  School District.  Workshops in areas such as literacy, mathematics, assessment, technology, differentiated instruction, curriculum mapping, special education and other best instructional practices are offered on an ongoing basis.  District committees monitor, review and revise curriculum  throughout the year.


The school has an active and vibrant PTA.   Some of the events that the PTA has sponsored each year have been a Fall Festival, Sweet Heart Dance and Holiday Shopping.  PTA fundraisers have helped teachers to purchase  technology, classroom items, provided support for field trips,  paid for enrichment assemblies, and invited artists in residence to the school.  Several years ago, the PTA raised over $60,000 to replace the school’s playground equipment.


East Derry Memorial Elementary School is a wonderful place for children to learn and grow.  The school’s success is reflective of the efforts of students, parents, educators, and other community members working together on behalf of children.

We begin our 2014-2015 school year with a lot of excitement.

In addition to our new kindergarten and first grade students, we anticipate all of the children to be excited and eager to learn.  Our fantastic faculty is also tremendously enthusiastic and motivated to help inspire your children learn and grow.  

South Range School continues to have a very active PTA and a strong volunteer program.  The PTA brings great opportunities to all of our students.  The PTA brings our school several cultural arts assemblies throughout the year.  They sponsor many evening socials and fun game nights.  The PTA helps reduce the families' out of pocket expense by partially funding field trips.  Also our volunteer program is just as strong as ever.  South Range School has been recognized for the  Blue Ribbon Volunteer Award annually over the past 30 years.  

We will begin our Good Citizenship program this year with three South Range expectations.
    1. Be Safe
    2. Be Respectful, Kind and Polite
    3. Do Your Best 
We feel that these are umbrella expectations that sum up all desired behaviors.  South Range students are always well behaved and considerate to others, however, it is always nice when you can make strong qualities stronger.  After the September focus on the three school expectations, we will continue the monthly focus and weekly quotes/reminders about attitudes, cooperation, friendships, respect, caring… 

At South Range School, we pride ourselves on our strong family-friendly bond and traditions.  We are considered to be a school where no one wants to leave.
As always, I invite you to call or stop in the office at anytime.

column11:
Welcome to Montessori Children’s Garden, an established Montessori preschool and kindergarten for children ages 2 ½  to 6 years in Goffstown, NH. Our school offers flexible hours, an indoor and outdoor curriculum and an atmosphere that nurtures self-concept and confidence.

The most important years of our children’s development and education occur at the beginning of their life.  This is when character, values, self-image, basic skills and knowledge, appreciation for culture and arts are formed.   The values and morals developed at this young age eventually evolve into deeper and more abstract concepts such as equity, freedom and justice.  At Montessori Children's Garden, these concepts are fundamental to the curriculum from day one.

The Granite YMCA, established in 1854, is part of the worldwide Y organization. The Y focuses on youth development, healthy living, and social responsibility. Across the country, Ys engage 21 million men, women and children – regardless of age, income or background – to improve the nation’s health and well-being, and provide opportunities to give back and support neighbors. Anchored in more than 10,000 communities, the Y has the long-standing relationships and physical presence not just to promise, but to deliver, lasting personal and social change.

column2: Learn As We Play Child Care Center
column11:
The name "Learn As We Play" evolved from the strong belief that children learn each day from playing. Whether it is free exploration through play or teacher guided play, children develop the necessary skills that they will need each day through play.

Here at Learn As We Play, we look forward to providing your family with a safe, loving, and nurturing environment in which your child can develop physically, emotionally, cognitively, and socially. Each of these developmental skills are fostered each day as the children have fun and learn at the same time.

Happy memories are among the best experiences children can take into the future. At Wonderworks Learning Center, we make those memories daily.

Located on the beautiful Greenfield campus of Crotched Mountain Rehabilitation Center, Wonderworks is a child-focused program where your child will grow, learn and explore. Since 1981, we've provided developmentally-appropriate educational opportunities for infants and children ages 6 months through 12 years, whether it's learning about animals, singing songs, sharing a story, making new friends or discovering the outdoors. Our caregivers nurture the whole child, providing kindness, creativity and compassion.

 When children are cared for intellectually, emotionally, physically and socially, they thrive. We understand; that's why we want to help your child find wonder in their day.

Hollis Preschool offers programs designed for families who want a part-time first school experience in a safe, stimulating, and nurturing environment. The goal of our preschool is to give children learning experiences that are meaningful to them at developmentally appropriate levels. At the heart of our philosophy is the need to foster the social, emotional, and physical growth of your child.

Our play-based program is centered on the premise that children learn best by doing. Children are guided and directed by the teacher through both structured activities and self-directed play. This allows the children to develop skills they need to participate in a group, as well as ample opportunity to explore and experiment independently with the wide range of materials set out each day. Using the guidelines established by the National Association for Education of Young Children (NAEYC), teachers develop curriculum around various learning themes. Within a theme, activities are planned to help children develop skills in all areas: social and emotional, language, science, math, imagination, art, music, and gross and fine motor. The classroom atmosphere is one of cooperation and mutual respect in which our children can play, learn, and thrive.

Located in New Hampshire, Hollis Academy for Children has been in business for over 30 years. We have earned respect for our fully licensed child care center and private school. Certified teachers offer year-round classes; full, half, and quarter days, before and after school care, and vacation and summer programs for youngsters of 30 months to age 12.

Founded in 1987, Hollis Academy for Children was a one-room school, and has since been expanded to provide our students with a quality education. Our open door policy for families keeps the line of communication honest. Our staff is involved in continuous education, and provide a developmentally appropriate curriculum in a structured environment. We take pride in an overall ratio of 1:7. We invite you to call for more information and to visit us, soon!

Merrimack PTA Kindergarten and Preschool is a private, non-profit organization established in 1961 under the auspices of the Parent Teacher Association of the Merrimack School District.

The educational philosophy of the Merrimack PTA Kindergarten and Preschool is to promote the total development of each child and respect individual differences. When children expand their horizons beyond the familiar home, every detail and impression is of essence to their successful adjustment. PTA Kindergarten and Preschool is like an extended family and home, with an ideal setting, a school house built with children’s needs in mind. We are a staff dedicated to nurture children’s joy for learning and self confidence, a close knit community where parents, teachers, and children learn, work, and play together.

The guidance and learning of each child in the early years is of extreme importance for the rest of his/her life. The goal of St. James Preschool Learning Center is to help young children develop socially and emotionally, as well as intellectually and physically. Children are motivated to enjoy learning and to grow more confident in their own abilities.

Our spacious learning center encourages both indoor and outdoor learning and playtime throughout a variety of programs.  Each class has their own classrooms, reading and play rooms. Children are able to go outside most school days and enjoy our newer playground equipment facilities.  On rainy days, we focus on gross motor skills inside the large Fellowship Hall.
