Our program is geared specifically towards the needs of a child, with regard to their social/emotional, physical motor, and cognitive development. The environment encourages their natural curiosity and self-confidence in exploring new situations.

 Essex Hollow Playschool, Inc. provides a developmental preschool program, in addition to quality childcare. Many of our activities are done in a multi-age setting, although group time is set aside each morning when the children are divided into groups by age. Our goal is to provide a program that will fit each child's needs, as differing as they are from one another, rather than having the child fit the program.

 Children construct their own knowledge by acting upon the world around them - it is not just a matter of reproducing what is presented to them. Through learning centers, the children have an ample amount of time to do just this. Our centers provide open-ended activities, allowing the children to use and practice basic motor skills, experiment at their own pace, and question what is happening. They will be able to look at all the possibilities whether they work or not. After all, mistakes are a valuable part of the learning process. We want to provide the children with an enriched environment, which will give them the opportunity to make choices, challenge, and provide them with the feeling that they are capable, competent, and responsible young individuals.

The Northwest Technical Center (NWTC) is a regional technical center located in St. Albans, Vermont. Our primary function is to serve 10th, 11th, and 12th grade students from Bellows Free Academy, Missisquoi Valley Union High School, and other interested students from the surrounding areas. NWTC also offers courses and programs to adult students–high school student graduates, as well as non-graduates–who are interested in continuing their technical education. 

There are eleven programs to choose from at NWTC.  Each program is offered in a two or three year sequence, meeting one to three periods per day, five days a week. The second year is a continuation of the first year, but offers advanced work and some specialization. The third year of a program is an optional year for students. They can choose to do an independent study, complete a third year of the classroom program, or work toward an on-the-job placement in their chosen field. Students enrolled in NWTC programs may receive equivalent credit in Math, Science and/or art. Some programs have agreements with area colleges that grant transcripted college credit (dual enrollment). All programs stress development of good work habits and desirable on-the-job behavior.

KinderStart is far more than childcare. We are a NAEYC (National Association for the Education of Young Children) accredited early education facility. Our staff is comprised of professional, certified, and licensed teachers. KinderStart provides a daily schedule based on the Creative Curriculum, Teaching Strategies Gold, Ages and Stages, as well as Vermont Early Learning Standards. We offer a high quality learning environment based on NAEYC standards, earning us 5 STARs in the STep Ahead Recognition Program. 

KinderStart is a small organization, in a familiar setting, enabling your child to feel more at home and allowing for a more personalized approach to child development. KinderStart collaborates with the community to explore enrichment opportunities and supports its professional staff by funding all professional seminars designed to increase the qualifications of its teachers. KinderStart teachers work in partnership with families, establishing and maintaining regular, ongoing communication, using a variety of resources to share vision, mission goals and expected child outcomes.

The community at KinderStart preschool looks forward to enjoying a fun and fulfilling early childcare experience with your family!

column11:
Our Philosophy
    We believe that children have a diversity of talents; we customize/personalize curriculum to support their achievements.
    We believe that each child who comes to us is an individual who brings both their strengths and their weaknesses with them. We honor each child’s unique differences and accommodate their social, emotional, and academic needs to the best of our abilities.
    We believe children are able to learn through observation, experimentation and exploration. By offering our children a safe place to explore and reflect; we feel they will develop a stronger understanding of academic principles and be able to make personal connections to the curriculum.
    We believe that children benefit from not only playing with their peers but also through group discussion, formal lessons and activities. We structure our day so children get the benefits of all aspects of our learning environment.
    We believe that when children are allowed to explore the natural world they can create a deeper understanding and appreciation for the world around them. children will spend time outside of the school challenging themselves physically, mentally and emotionally.
    We believe that education should create the circumstances for which our students to show their true selves. We create the conditions under which each student will flourish as individuals that will complement the whole of their community.

The Heartworks and Renaissance Schools were founded in 1988 by Diane Rooney and Louise H. Piché and by 2013 had grown to encompass three Heartworks Preschools, in Burlington, Williston and Shelburne along with the Renaissance Elementary School at Shelburne Farms. 

In September 2013, Lisa and Paul Zengilowski assumed ownership of the schools. They have a rich and varied history with the school, initially as parents, whose children Gregory and Allison attended Heartworks and Renaissance Schools through sixth grade. Lisa designed and inaugurated several programs at Renaissance including;  

    Renaissance Summer Enrichment Academy 
    Renaissance Full Moon Family Campfire 
    Renaissance Annual Yearbook

In 2002, Lisa joined the organization as the first School Director for Heartworks Williston and held that position from 2002-2012; she was instrumental in growing the school from four classes to nine classes including expanding to Kindergarten through Second grade classes during 2003-2007.  In 2011, she assumed operational responsibility for all Heartworks Preschools, a role she held until assuming ownership in September, 2013.

The schools expanded in the Fall of 2014 to include the Infant/Toddler Program, the Endeavour Middle School – Sixth through Eighth grades, as well as Heartworks School in Stowe.

Each school name was chosen with care and reflects education appropriate to the developmental stages of the children.

column11:
“Children are at the heart of all we do. We strive to nurture a child’s curiosity, ignite their enthusiasm for exploring, and help them develop tools for inquiry, invention and achievement.  In that quest, we welcome families and others into a community-wide collaboration to help our children become their best selves—responsible citizens and stewards of the greater world, and builders of the future.”

What distinguishes an elementary school and makes it unique?  Here at the Village School of North Bennington, we strive every day to answer that question.

Creating a school that is warm and caring and helps our students to be “interested in life” is our first objective.  But beyond that, we want everyone who walks through our doors—teachers, parents, staff, volunteers—to feel the sense of excitement and enthusiasm that has blossomed here at VSNB since its rebirth as an independent town academy, in 2013.

 It’s a part of our philosophy that children who feel safe, secure, and nurtured will be successful learners. Toward that goal, rather than simply providing an atmosphere of education, VSNB creates an environment for education based on the mission above.

Welcome to Milton’s Elite Childcare. We thank you for looking in to our program for your family. We would like you to know that our program is a “hands on” structured play based childcare center. Our staff family will help guide your child’s daily journey as they learn to communicate with one another in a positive and structured manner. Each child is unique so our curriculum is also taught with this in mind. Not everyone learns in the same way but rest assured, our owners and staff will work together to help your child achieve their personal and education goals.

It is our desire to be hands on owners and would like to be as much a part of the classrooms as possible in that helping capacity. It’s import to us that not only do your children know we are a part of their learning but the staff and families we serve know that we are a part of it as well and can come to us at any time and we will be able to help because we know these children as much as they/you do.Our goals are; *To encourage independence and exploration through movement, music, play, art and language *To create opportunities to use imagination *To learn constructive ways to express emotions *To appreciate diverse cultural, personal and social environments regardless of race, color, age, sex or handicap *To make each child’s daily experience a positive one.

In particular, the Dothan Brook School strives to reach out to the community to build relationships that create a rich and relevant curriculum for our students.  These school community partnerships include

    A thriving Parent Teacher Organization.

column11:
Bellwether is an exciting place. For students, it’s a place that honors their unique learning journeys and invites exploration, inquiry and reflection. For teachers, it’s a place that allows them to teach with vigor and intensity while enjoying a playfulness and improvisation that many schools seem to have lost sight of. For families and friends, it’s a place that celebrates relationships and community - one whose doors are always open.

Our website is a virtual extension of Bellwether, designed to both educate those who seek to learn more about us and holistic education and to support thoughtful, dynamic communication within and beyond the School community.  We hope this site helps to promote a deep understanding of the unique education we offer at Bellwether where we are guided by our mission to create a community that honors student voice and nurtures engaged citizens. I also invite you to learn more about holistic education in an interview with me here.

So, whether you are new to holistic education or are already a Bellwether family, I invite you to look around. I hope you discover not only the information that you are looking for, but the spirit of our learning community as well.

column11:
Our school is home to approximately 411 children and families.  Our average class size is 16 children per class.  The core areas of curriculum include the Common Core State Standards (CCSS) for English Language Arts (writing, reading, speaking and listening), math, science, and social studies.  In addition, all children enjoy enhanced learning opportunities through weekly specials instruction in the areas of art, music, physical education, and technology.  We also have a full service library with brand new shelving that houses over 12,000 books for children.  

Derby Elementary is a technology rich environment, with interactive boards and document cameras in every classroom, three mobile laptop carts, 2 computer labs, 24 Kindles, access to an online library for downloadable books,25 Playaway audio books and a 15,000 volume leveled book room for classroom instruction.  In addition, all fourth - sixth graders are assigned their own Chromebook to use in the classroom.  Our teachers are integrating technology into instruction more and more every day in an effort in increase engagement and prepare children for the world of work in the 21st Century and beyond. 

I feel honored to have the privilege of being part of such an amazing school.  Derby Elementary is a beautiful school, but the real treasures are found within its doors…..children that are eager to learn.  The high-caliber teachers and support staff continually seek out opportunities to engage learners in new and exciting ways.  Together, they build a kind, tolerant, accepting learning community that focuses on success for all children.  High standards, mixed with fun, memorable experiences are a recipe for success at Derby.

At Annette's Preschool, our philosophy of early childhood education is based on two very strong beliefs. First and foremost, our staff believes that each and every child is a unique individual capable of learning and success! We provide an inclusive setting that recognizes and caters to children's varied abilities, needs, and learning styles. We believe that to create such an inclusive setting, we must provide the children with balance.

In addition, our staff believes that young children thrive and learn best in an environment that is nurturing, stimulating, and provides a variety of developmentally appropriate experiences and materials intended for the “whole child”. We believe that children learn best through meaningful play and exploration, and encourage a balance of child-centered activities with teacher-instructed curriculum. Our programs integrates curriculum that encourages social, physical, emotional, and creative growth. We believe in positive language, active problem solving, appropriate and defined limits, and positive consequences for desired behaviors.

As teachers it is our duty to serve as positive role models and facilitators, to create empathetic and caring classrooms, and to stay updated with our trainings and certifications to ensure best practice. We believe in the power of love, understanding, acceptance, exploration, autonomy, and balance.

column2: Salisbury Community School After School Program

column11:
Overview
The Family Place is a parent-child center located in Norwich, VT. We proudly serve the entire Upper Valley region of Vermont and New Hampshire. In 2015, we will celebrate 30 years of helping our community, from 1985-2015.
Our Mission
The Family Place delivers comprehensive programs designed to strengthen positive relationships, teach essential skills and promote enduring healthy growth for families with young children in the Upper Valley and surrounding communities.

When we opened in 2010, TAKE FIVE was simply a drop-in childcare center set up to offer an option of childcare for a few hours while parents (whom we expected would be primarily from out of town) enjoyed some adult time. Very soon after opening, we discovered that not only were the majority of our clients local families, but also that they wanted scheduled care without the traditional year-long contracts expected at other centers.

We also were approached about formalizing a program for 2 year old children; in essence combining daycare and preschool (set preschool program with the option to add childcare time before or after the structured curriculum). Using a theme based curriculum from years past, we jumped right in and by the spring of 2011 had completed our first year of an “Introduction to Preschool” program. Throughout the year we had tweaked and changed elements of the curriculum to be more age appropriate for our 2 year olds and worked on preparing a plan for the next year.

Our 2011/2012 school year included a lot of growth and many additions to our preschool curriculum. We also spent quite a bit of time reevaluating what we wanted to be and how we wanted to define TAKE FIVE. From those discussions it became clear we really enjoyed the preschool program and wanted to expand it. However, we still wanted to be able to offer flexible care to people.

column2: Midd Summer Lunch and Recreation Program
column11:
Our mission is to teach kids about agriculture, nutrition, and the importance of locally grown food. We do this by having the children
work in their own garden, participate in weekly cooking classes, and help prepare a majority of their own meals. Children also learn the importance of exercise by engaging in a wide varieties of activities. Campers participate in hiking, calm-water kayaking, swimming, indoor rock climbing, yoga and cooperative games. Each summer our campers complete a community service project. The educational mission of Richford Elementary School focuses upon the student as an individual and as a contributing member of the school community.  It is important that we prepare our children for the future as productive members of society.

column2: South Burlington Early Essential Ed Preschool @ Chamberlin School

column11:
We believe children are born with a desire to explore and understand the natural world, and that early experiences with nature set a precedent for lifelong learning and well-being.

We provide children with special nature-centered opportunities to learn about themselves, the world, life.

We develop curriculum in response to students' interests.  We offer students a range of "real" materials--water, soil, rocks, plants, snow.  Balch children learn by doing; they play in the mud, climb on logs, follow insects, and plant seeds.

By guiding young children to connect with the natural world in our nurturing, hands-on, discovery-oriented program, we seek to inspire a lifelong love of nature, and foster a lasting environmental ethic.                                        
The Balch Nature School at the Fairbanks Museum is committed to supporting and building on the child's innate interest in exploring the natural world.

It is the goal of our school community to work collaboratively with students, parents and other members of the community to build relationships and promote effective communication. In 1970 a group of Middlebury residents decided that the community needed a safe supportive program for the children of families who needed to work outside of the home. They wanted to ensure that children, particularly the children of struggling single mothers, were being well cared for.

Today that program, Mary Johnson Children's Center, is a leader in early childhood education both in the county and in the state. The Center is home to several programs which support children and families. Reflecting the goals of its founders, the Center strives to meet the needs of working families who use the Center and who represent the economic and cultural diversity of our community.
